
[1]meditate

   MED'ITATE, v.i. [L. meditor.]

   1. To dwell on any thing in thought; to contemplate; to study; to turn
   or revolve any subject in the mind; appropriately but not exclusively
   used of pious contemplation, or a consideration of the great truths of
   religion.

   His delight is in the law of the Lord, and in his law doth he meditate
   day and night. Ps.1.

   2. To intend; to have in contemplation.

   I meditate to pass the remainder of life in a state of undisturbed
   repose.

      MED'ITATE, v.t. To plan by revolving in the mind; to contrive; to
                                   intend.

   Some affirmed that I meditated a war.

   1. To think on; to revolve in the mind.

   Blessed is the man that doth meditate good things.
